# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: akiko-aoyagi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:akiko-aoyagi/8th-continent] 8th Continent is available in Regular Original and Vanilla, Complete Vanilla, Light Original, Vanilla and Chocolate, Fat Free Original and Vanilla.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/8th-continent] 8th Continent is also lactose free, gluten free, and certified Vegan.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/8th-continent] The 8th Continent worldwide headquarters is located in Santa Ana, California.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-breeze-harper] Harper attributes her initial interest in practicing veganism to the influence of the work of Dick Gregory in connecting diet to the liberation struggle of marginalized groups, and to Afrocentric, raw foodist Queen Afua.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-breeze-harper] In 2015, Harper organized a conference, *The Vegan Praxis of Black Lives Matters*, to discuss intersectional issues concerning veganism and the Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-breeze-harper] In the same year, Harper joined the advisory board for *Black Vegans Rock*.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-breeze-harper] Harper was the Humane Party's vice-presidential nominee for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] In 1893, Cole prepared a set of vegetarian menus that received high commendation at the Universal Cookery Exhibition.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] The menus were later published as "Menus for a Week in November" in Rachel Swain's *Swain Cookery* and in Florence I.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] Nicholson's *The Jubilee Cookery Book: Vegetarian Recipes*.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] Cole worked in several London vegetarian organisations.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] Tovey in founding the Battersea, Clapham and Wandsworth Vegetarian Society, with A.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] She was a committee member of the Women's Vegetarian Union and gave a cookery lesson for the union at the offices of the Vegetarian Federal Union in 1898.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] According to James Gregory, Cole worked as an assistant to Nicholson and later to Charlotte Despard.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] She succeeded Nicholson as editor of *The Children's Realm*.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] By 1914, she was honorary secretary of the Vegetarian Federal Union.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] Cole gave public talks and demonstrations on vegetarian cookery.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] In 1910, as secretary of the West London Vegetarian Society, she gave a cookery demonstration at a vegetarian dinner held by the society at Pirbright Hall, Southfields.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] In 1913, as honorary secretary of the London Vegetarian Society, she spoke on "What is Vegetarianism" at a meeting at the Adult School in Sutton.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] In July 1915, *The Jewish Chronicle* published an interview with Cole, then secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, on vegetarianism and Jewish dietary practice.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] She argued that a vegetarian diet was compatible with Jewish religious observance and discussed food economy during the First World War.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] In 1917, when described as a former organising secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, she gave cookery demonstrations for the Food and Cookery Association in Southampton, where she presented vegetarian menus and methods for reducing food waste.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] Cole was listed as secretary of the Children's Dinner Fund in 1916.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] Hilda Kean writes that Nicholson established the fund for underfed children, distributing cheap meals of vegetable soup, wholemeal bread, and wholemeal currant bread.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-m-cole] In 1921, Cole was honorary secretary and organiser of the Women's Freedom League Settlement in Nine Elms, which provided daily penny and halfpenny hot meals for more than 100 children and operated a milk depot.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Veigele held posts in the Women's Vegetarian Union, served on the editorial and executive committees of the Vegetarian Federal Union, and contributed to the feminist periodical *Shafts*.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] In 1896 she founded the Women's International Progressive Union.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] She later helped establish vegetarian organisations abroad, including the *Société Belge pour l'étude de la réforme alimentaire* in Brussels in 1897 and the Dublin Society for the Study of Food Reform in 1899.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] She died by suicide in 1915 after years of illness and financial hardship.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Veigele was born in Paris around 1862 to John and Alexandrine Veigele.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] She moved with her family to London in 1866, when she was five.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Her mother adopted a vegetarian diet in 1888 and became active in the vegetarian movement and women's rights.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Veigele taught French and music to support herself and her mother.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] From February 1894 she advertised tuition in the feminist magazine *Shafts*.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] In 1898 she contributed an article to the magazine titled "Qualities admired by Men in Women and by Women in Men".
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] The Women's Vegetarian Union (WVU) was founded in London in March 1895 by Veigele's mother, Alexandrine.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Veigele served as honorary superintendent of an agency depot connected with the organisation, and later as assistant secretary and honorary secretary.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] James Gregory describes the WVU as a forum for women involved in food reform and moral education.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Veigele was a member of the Vegetarian Federal Union's editorial and executive committees.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Other committee members included Henry B.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] In February 1896 Veigele founded the Women's International Progressive Union in London and served as its secretary.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] The organisation was described as non-political and non-sectarian.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] It sought to promote women's participation in educational and social work through lectures and discussions, and held 21 meetings in its first year.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Her mother was also involved in its administration.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Veigele attended the Congrès féministe international ("International Feminist Congress") in Brussels in 1897.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] While there, she established the Société Belge pour l'étude de la réforme alimentaire ("Belgian Society for the Study of Food Reform"), which sought to bring together supporters of vegetarianism in Belgium.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] The society soon began publishing a bimonthly periodical, **La Réforme alimentaire**, edited by M.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] In 1899 Veigele helped establish the Dublin Society for the Study of Food Reform, working with Mrs.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Sophia Gough, a fellow vegetarian and the wife of the proprietor of Gough's Temperance Hotel on Exchequer Street, Dublin.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] In the 1901 United Kingdom census, Veigele and her mother were recorded as naturalised British subjects.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Veigele's later years were affected by illness and financial hardship.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Her mother died in 1913 after experiencing poverty and the effects of her daughter's illness, while attempting to establish a boarding house.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] After her mother's death, Veigele was reported to have moved to St John's Home in London and later entered the workhouse, before being admitted to an asylum.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] Veigele died by suicide by hanging at her cottage in Crowthorne, where she had lived for about two months, between 29 May and 2 June 1915; she was 53.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] A newspaper report of the inquest gave the date as about 31 May 1915.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] The coroner read a letter found at the scene in which Veigele attributed her state of mind to prolonged illness, poverty and dependence and wrote that she no longer felt able to endure her circumstances.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/adrienne-veigele] The jury returned a verdict of "Suicide while of unsound mind".
[src:akiko-aoyagi/agedashi-tofu] While *agedashi dōfu* is the best-known *agedashi* dish, some other dishes may be prepared with similar techniques.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/agedashi-tofu] These include *agedashinasu* (揚げ出し茄子), using eggplant.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Akiko Aoyagi was born in Tokyo, Japan, on January 24, 1950.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] She attended the Quaker Friends School and then the Women's College of the Arts, where she studied Fashion Design.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] After graduation, she worked as a fashion designer in Tokyo, where she lightened her hair and wore "tie-dye maxi-skirts." She was frustrated, however, as she found herself in "a pressure-packed, highspeed job and I did not like it.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] It was a superficial, very exhausting life which I wanted to change.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] I wanted to go to Africa with the Peace Corps." She also thought of becoming a Catholic nun.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] In 1971, her sister set Aoyagi up on a blind date with William Shurtleff (an American who was a student of Suzuki Roshi at the Tassajara Zen Mountain Center, and was in Japan in order to help Roshi set up a center).
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Shurtleff was her sister's classmate in a Japanese class at a university in Tokyo.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] They discovered that they shared interests in Zen meditation.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Ultimately, Shurtleff did not return to Tassajara, and Aoyagi "sold all her clothes, quit the fashion company, and moved in with him." They began to hitchhike together throughout Japan, and talked about traveling to India to visit ashrams.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] During that same time period in 1971, Shurtleff read the (then) recently released *Diet for a Small Planet* by Frances Moore Lappé, which argued that soybeans were a superior source of protein.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Using Lappe's book as a reference, Shurtleff wanted to learn more about Tofu.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Aoyagi later noted that although she had grown up with Tofu, ("just like you grow up with bread in this country"), Shurtleff's interest in it gave her a new appreciation for the art of Tofu production.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Aoyagi introduced Shurtleff to "Kyoto's Haute cuisine Tofu restaurants" where a 12-course meal was about three dollars.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] In 1972, they signed a book contract with Nahum and Beverly Stiskin, who ran the small independent publishing company Autumn Press (which published books on macrobiotics and the Shinto religion).
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Shurtleff apprenticed with "tofu master," Toshio Arai, to learn traditional approaches to tofu production, and was sometimes joined by Aoyagi.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Next, they came to the United States and traveled around the country in a Dodge Ram van to publicize both books.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] They gave interviews, met countercultural communities, and visited Zen centers.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Aoyagi later remembered the experience of sixty-four stops in four months as "grueling." They also visited the vegan-based intentional community, The Farm, as Shurtleff had previously been in communication with them about Tempeh production, and had a chance to study it while there.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] The successful tour led to high book sales.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] In addition, in 1979, they published *The Book of Tempeh* (1979).
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] In 1975, Aoyagi and Shurtleff co-founded the New Age Foods Study Center (in Tokyo and California), where they tested recipes and distributed information on soy.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Aoyagi and Shurtleff were married, but later divorced in the early 1990s.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Food writer Jonathan Kauffman states in *Hippie Food: How Back-To-The-Landers, Longhairs, and Revolutionaries Changed the Way We Eat* (2018), that Tofurky developed due to the influence of Frances Moore Lappé, Aoyagi and Shurtleff, and The Farm.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] He also credits the rise of tofu shops, tofu cookbooks, and vegetarian cookbooks that use tofu in the West to Aoyagi and Shurtleff.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Barry begins the chapter on Aoyagi and Shurtleff by asserting that in 1975, "few Americans had even the vaguest idea of what it [Tofu] was.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Now [in 1995] it is sold in countless supermarkets and health food stores, and its name as well as its substance is on everyone's lips.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Credit for this extraordinary surge in popularity must go to William Shurtleff and his Tokyo-born wife, Akiko Aoyagi.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] They are the co-authors of *The Book of Tofu* which has become the bible for tofu enthusiasts." "The Rynn Berry Jr.
[src:akiko-aoyagi/akiko-aoyagi] Aoyagi and Shurtleff have 66 books in print.
